\section{Mathematical Business Logic}
The program works in a way that when a user or household owner makes a
deposit(money), M, it deducts a maintenance fee, Fm of 500UGX and the
balance(grossAmount), Mnet is used to calculate the units bought by
dividing by the dynamicRate (for either domestic or commercial meter).
The mathematical evaluation is modeled below:

\subsection{Calculation of Gross Amount}
\begin{quote}
Given a gross money M, the processing grossAmount Mnet is computed after
a fixed maintenance fee (Fm) extraction:
If M less than Fm, the operational routine flags an immediate structural
evaluation error and terminates execution.
\end{quote}
$$M_{\text{net}} = M - F_m$$

\subsection{Calculating Number of Credit Units}
\begin{quote}
The final number of credit units (U) are scaled dynamically based on a
string mapping logical condition checking account categories:
Where: Dynamicrate = 250.0 UGX, if Type ='' Commercial''

150.0 UGX, if Type ='' Domestic''
\end{quote}
$$\Delta U = \frac{M_{\text{net}}}{\text{DynamicRate}}$$

\section{General operation of the program}

\begin{enumerate}
\def\labelenumi{\roman{enumi}.}


\item
  \textbf{All-in-One Variable}: We created a custom struct to tie a
  user\textquotesingle s ID, Name, Account Type, Balance, and Usage
  together.
\item
  \textbf{Account Type Flag}: A simple number identifies whether the
  user is Domestic or Commercial.
\item
  \textbf{Login Gatekeeper:} A basic login function checks the user
  before showing the main menu.
\item
  \textbf{Master PIN:} The system is protected by a simple access pin.
\item
  \textbf{Pass or Fail:} If the password is right, it returns 1 to
  unlock the app; otherwise, it closes down.
\item
  \textbf{Continuous Loop:} The program keeps running inside a loop so
  the admin can do multiple tasks without restarting.
\item
  \textbf{Menu Routing:} A switch-case block takes the
  user\textquotesingle s choice (1 to 7) and jumps directly to that
  specific task.
\item
  \textbf{Wrong Input Guard}: If someone types a wrong number or letter,
  the program catches it and asks them to try again.
\item
  \textbf{Registering Users}: Before adding a new household, the code
  checks if the list is full or if the ID already exists.
\item
  \textbf{Searching by ID}: A basic for loop goes through the list one
  by one to find the matching ID.
\item
  \textbf{Not Found Warning:} If the loop finishes and finds nothing, it
  safely tells the admin the record doesn\textquotesingle t exist.
\item
  \textbf{Editing Info:} Once an ID is matched, the admin can directly
  type over the old name or update the daily water usage\textbf{.}
\item
  \textbf{Deleting a Record:} To remove someone, the program locates
  their spot and slides all the remaining names up by one index to fill
  the gap.
\item
  \textbf{Updating the Count:} The system automatically lowers the total
  user count so it doesn\textquotesingle t leave blank spaces in the
  memory.

\end{enumerate}
\section{Main Requirements of the Program}

\begin{enumerate}
\def\labelenumi{\roman{enumi}.}
\item
  To receive household information and store it using structures.
\item
  To be able to edit, update and delete the household information.
\item
  To calculate the number of credit units depending on how much a user
  has input.
\item
  The program should print a receipt after the calculation of the credit
  units showing the units purchased and the balance of units.
\item
  It should be able to print the summary of records of households stored
  in the system showing all their details including credit units and
  balance.
\item
  The program should be able to detect leakage and low credit balance
  and display an appropriate error or warning message.
\end{enumerate}

